# StewartOptimizer v2 — Round 4 changes (optional servo capability specs)

This round adds optional servo torque and speed inputs to the optimizer.
The optimizer's existing `torque` and `speedDemand` metrics tell you what
each candidate layout *requires* of its servos. With this round, you can
also tell the optimizer what your servo *delivers*, and it will report
margin per layout — letting you filter out layouts your hardware can't
actually drive.

This is intentionally **soft**, not a hard constraint. Layouts that
exceed your servo specs still appear on the Pareto front, just flagged
"⚠ OVER". You can see them and decide whether to upgrade the servo or
back off the workspace requirements.

## Two operating modes

**Mode A — "What servo do I need?"** (specs left blank)
Same behavior as before. `torque` is the peak torque each servo will
need to deliver at the worst-case workspace pose. `speedDemand` is the
peak angular velocity needed at the cycling frequency. The result panel
labels these as "min servo spec" so you know what to shop for.

**Mode B — "Will my servo handle it?"** (specs filled in)
The optimizer additionally computes:
- `torqueMargin = (servoMaxTorqueNm − torque) / servoMaxTorqueNm`
- `speedMargin  = (servoMaxSpeed − speedDemand) / servoMaxSpeed`

Positive values = headroom (e.g. 0.30 means the layout uses 70% of your
servo's capacity). Zero = at the limit. Negative = exceeds it. The
result panel shows the demand alongside your spec ("τ 1.20/1.50 N·m
(20% margin)") and warns visually if margin is negative.

## What changed in the code

- **`requirements.js`**: `parseRequirements()` now reads optional
  `constraints.servo_max_torque_nm` (N·m) and
  `constraints.servo_max_speed_deg_per_sec` (°/s). Absent or 0 → null.
- **`optimizer.js`**: `Optimizer` constructor accepts `servoMaxTorqueNm`
  and `servoMaxSpeedRadPerS` (note: rad/s internally). `evaluateLayout()`
  computes `torqueMargin` and `speedMargin` (or null if specs unset)
  and includes them in the metrics object alongside `servoMaxTorqueNm`
  and `servoMaxSpeedRadPerS` for downstream display.
- **`optimizer-worker.js`**: receives `servoMaxTorqueNm` (N·m) and
  `servoMaxSpeedDegPerS` (°/s) from the UI, converts speed deg/s → rad/s,
  passes both to the Optimizer. Margins and reference values are
  serialized into the Pareto payload.
- **`index.html`**: new "Servo Specs (optional)" section after Safety,
  with `Servo Max Torque (N·m)` and `Servo Max Speed (°/s)` inputs.
  Tooltips include conversion notes (kg·cm → N·m, datasheet "0.16s/60°"
  → °/s, derate by 30–50% for under-load cycling). Pareto chart
  dropdowns gain "Torque Margin" and "Speed Margin" axes. Result-info
  line auto-switches between "minimum servo spec" mode and
  "demand/spec margin" mode based on whether specs are entered.

## Selection pressure (what the GA actually optimizes)

I deliberately did NOT change the optimizer's objective vector based
on whether servo specs are given. With or without specs, the compact
4-objective set is still `coverage, isotropy, limitMargin, −torque`.
This is intentional:

- Mathematically, minimizing torque demand and maximizing torque margin
  produce the same Pareto ordering when the servo spec is constant —
  margin = (spec − demand) / spec is monotonically decreasing in demand,
  so layouts rank identically either way.
- Adding margin as a separate objective would push the optimizer toward
  high-margin layouts even when the user really just wanted "minimum
  spec." Keeping the objective unchanged means the optimizer behaves
  the same way; the spec affects display and filtering only.

If you want the optimizer to actively avoid over-spec layouts during
selection, that's a separate switch I can add — let me know.

## Conversion cheat-sheet (lives in the input tooltips too)

- **Torque** datasheet → N·m: divide kg·cm by 10.2. A 25 kg·cm servo ≈ 2.45 N·m.
- **Speed** datasheet → °/s: if the spec is "Xs / 60°", compute 60 / X. Example:
  "0.16 sec/60°" → 60 ÷ 0.16 = 375 °/s.
- **Derating**: datasheet speed is no-load. Real cycling speed under
  load is typically 50–70% of rated; conservative engineering uses 50%.
  If your servo specs say 375 °/s and you're driving a meaningful payload,
  enter ≈ 200 °/s rather than 375.

## Quick test plan

1. Open the optimizer. Both servo spec inputs are blank by default.
2. Run with default settings. Open the result panel — should read
   something like "τ demand 1.20 N·m (min servo spec) — speed demand
   240 °/s (min servo spec)".
3. Enter `1.5` in **Servo Max Torque (N·m)** and `300` in
   **Servo Max Speed (°/s)**. Click any Pareto point. The same line
   should now read "τ 1.20/1.50 N·m (20% margin) — speed 240/300 °/s
   (20% margin)".
4. Drop **Servo Max Torque** to `0.8`. The selected layout's torque
   margin goes negative — should now show "⚠ OVER" in the info line.
5. Switch the Pareto chart Y-axis to "Torque Margin" — points should
   spread out by margin. Layouts above 0 are within spec; below 0 exceed.
6. Run a fresh optimization with the specs entered. Pareto chart should
   include layouts with various margin values; you can pick one that
   meets your criteria.
